defaultRichard Gordondefault: You can keep that and in only one case, I think, has the Government not made a remedial order and that was because it was academic. I cannot remember the case now, but in every case the Government has ultimately acted.
defaultProfessor defaultMastermandefault: I think the declaration of incompatibility—or unconstitutionality as you might call it in the event of a written 
defaultconstitution
default—is an excellent proposal and something that deserves further thought. It is the remedy that effectively straddles the ideas of the rule of law and the ideas relating to 
defaultparliament
defaultary 
defaultsovereignty
default because it respects the democratic will of the legislature by not affecting the validity of the legislation—or at least not explicitly doing so—yet allows the courts to vindicate the rule of law by saying that there is an issue here of compatibility with the 
defaultconstitution
default or the convention rights or whatever objective standard you are hoping to balance legislation against. So it is the mechanism that arguably in theory allows for this dialogue, allows for 
defaulta collaboration
default between the branches of government, that does not necessarily result in one always having a trump card to play.
defaultDr defaultMurkensdefault: This dialogue is not just a matter of institutional comity; it is a matter of necessity because of the breadth of law. If we think about this, when 
defaultParliament
default legislates, it legislates for the nation. 
defaultParliament
default is the forum of the nation. It cannot ever anticipate all the individual repercussions that will emerge somewhere down the line. That is for the courts to solve. The courts are there to protect individual justice. That bias is ingrained in the judicial system. When the courts say that we have an issue here with individual justice that has emerged further down the line and 
defaultthat therefore shines a negative light on the integrity of the statute as a whole, the judges have to have some mechanism in which to say a 
defaultconstitution
defaultal issue has arisen. Right now—but only since 2000—that mechanism is built into the Human Rights Act. But as we say, and others have pointed out as well, we could create a common-law declaration of unconstitutionality that would preserve 
defaultparliament
defaultary 
defaultsovereignty
default but would also allow the judges to say an issue has emerged after the fact, and this is how we highlight it.
